{
  "analysis": "The shell prompt shows we're in a container at /app as root. No MySQL commands have been run yet and there is no database output provided. We need to discover whether a MySQL/MariaDB server is present and reachable, find a client and credentials (if any), and then wait for your question so I can run the single SQL statement you permit. Currently nothing has been accomplished toward connecting to MySQL.",
  "plan": "1) Check whether a mysql client is available (which mysql and mysql --version).\n2) Check whether a mysqld process is running (ps aux | grep mysqld).\n3) Inspect common MySQL runtime and configuration locations for sockets and credentials (/var/run/mysqld, /etc/mysql, /root/.my.cnf).\n4) If a socket or credentials are found, report findings so you can ask the SQL question; otherwise, we will proceed based on what's available. I will run only diagnostic shell commands now (no SQL).",
  "commands": [
    {
      "keystrokes": "which mysql\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "mysql --version\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "ps aux | grep -E 'mysqld|mariad' | grep -v grep\n",
      "duration": 0.5
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "ls -la /var/run/mysqld 2>/dev/null || true\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "ls -la /etc/mysql 2>/dev/null || true\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "cat /root/.my.cnf 2>/dev/null || true\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "env | grep -i mysql || true\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    }
  ],
  "task_complete": false
}

{
  "analysis": "The previous diagnostics show there is no mysql client installed (which mysql returned nothing and 'mysql --version' failed). There is also no mysqld/mariadb server process running, and common MySQL config/socket locations returned nothing. So currently we cannot run SQL because the client is missing and no local server is detected. To proceed we need a MySQL client available in the container (or access details for a remote server).",
  "plan": "1) Inspect the OS to choose a package manager (read /etc/os-release). 2) Check for common package managers (apt-get, yum, apk). 3) Look for any mysql/mariadb binaries in /usr/bin. 4) If apt-get exists, install a MySQL client (default-mysql-client) so we can run mysql commands. 5) Verify installation by running 'mysql --version'. After the client is available, I'll ask you for the database connection details or the SQL question to run one SQL statement as required. Commands that may take time (apt operations) will have a longer duration.",
  "commands": [
    {
      "keystrokes": "cat /etc/os-release\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "which apt-get\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "which yum\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "which apk\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "ls -la /usr/bin | grep -E 'mysql|mariadb' || true\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "apt-get update && apt-get install -y default-mysql-client\n",
      "duration": 20.0
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "mysql --version\n",
      "duration": 0.5
    }
  ],
  "task_complete": false
}
